  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and standards aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to create a global system for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities. Key international instruments and organizations include:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This was one of the first international agreements to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention includes provisions to combat money laundering associated with organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention addresses money laundering related to corruption.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n   - **FATF Recommendations:** The FATF\u2019s 40 Recommendations provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures. These recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) that require member states to implement specific AML measures. The **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which came into effect in December 2020, strengthens criminal sanctions and expands the scope of money laundering offenses.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, emphasizing the importance of customer due diligence (CDD) and Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures.\n\n### 5. **Wolfsberg Group**\n   - This group of global banks has developed anti-money laundering principles, particularly for private banking, which are widely recognized as best practices.\n\n### 6. **Egmont Group**\n   - This is a network of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) around the world that collaborate to combat money laundering and terrorist financing by sharing financial intelligence.\n\n### 7. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These institutions play a role in assisting countries with implementing AML/CFT measures through technical assistance and compliance monitoring.\n\n### 8. **Bilateral and Multilateral Agreements**\n   - Countries often enter into bilateral or multilateral agreements to cooperate in the investigation and prosecution of money laundering cases, including mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and extradition agreements.\n\n### Key Principles in International AML Laws:\n   - **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Making money laundering a criminal offense.\n   - **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Requiring financial institutions to verify the identity of their customers and understand the nature of their transactions.\n   - **Reporting Suspicious Activities:** Mandating that financial institutions report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.\n   - **Record-Keeping:** Ensuring that financial institutions maintain records of transactions for a specified period.\n   - **International Cooperation:** Encouraging countries to cooperate in the investigation and prosecution of money laundering cases.\n\nWhile these international laws and standards provide a framework, individual countries are responsible for implementing them through their own legal systems. Compliance with these standards is often monitored through mutual evaluations conducted by organizations like the FATF.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
